Has the World Become a Better Place?

By Joey Hayden

INTRODUCTION

As the world entered the 21st century, technology and online media has slowly come to dominate our lives. Every day we are bombarded by news of wars, terrorism, domestic inequality, corruption, homocides, and political instability. However, many others, such as Steven Pinker have proposed that despite the bleak image that the media has painted, the world at large has in fact been improving over the last few centuries, and most drastically in the last few decades. This makes us ask, which view is correct? Has the world improved, despite the many horrors we regularly hear of in the news? Most of has have heard of the military buildup in China, the Russian takeover of Crimea and of the domestic political violence in the US. Despite these events and the many other problems we hear of so often, have the lives of the average human on Earth improved? Or have certain countries improved as others are left in the dust? Or perhaps, is the news correct and the world is headed in a downward spiral? Using a number of data sets from various 3rd party organizations, I will attempt to shed some light on whether or not the world at large has improved for the average citizen with various measures from economic stability and freedom to happiness, poverty, homocides rates and other statistical measures.

How Do You Measure Human Progress?

If we want to determine if the world has become a better place through data, we first need to figure out what we need to look for. I have decided a 6 different values, some of them are index's representing a number of different measures, while others are independent measurements. For example, the Economic Freedom Summary Index is created based on 12 different measures of economic freedom, whereas the Homocide rate is a single measurement. Below, I have listed each of the values I will be using for this analysis, along with what they represent.

List of Values Used to Judge Human Progress

  • Development Index
  • Homocide Rate
  • Hunger Index
  • Cantril Happiness Scale
  • Gender Pay Gap Comparison
  • Economic Freedom Index

Development Index

The Development Index uses life expectancy, access to education, and standard of living to generate an index value representing the total development of the culture, government, and average life of a citizen.

Homocide Rate

The Homocide Rate is the number of homocides per 100,000 individuals in the country. It is a rate, not a number, hence it scales with the size of the country in question.

Hunger Index

The Hunger Index measures how well the caloric and nutritional requirements are met in a specific country to generate a value. The difference between nutrition and caloric requirements are an important thing to note. An individual could have more than enough calories to survive, but lack necessary vitamins and minerals leading to sickness, disease, or even death in extreme cases.

Cantril Happiness Scale

The Cantril Happiness data is a scale where respondents are asked to rate their lives on a scale from 1-10, where 10 is the happiest, and 1 is the most depressed.

Gender Pay Gap Comparison

The Gender Pay Gap Comparison (Equality measure) is the percent difference between the wages of men and women in various countries over time.

Economic Freedom Index

The Economic Data has many different measures, but what I will be looking at is the Economic Freedom Summary Index, a measure of how free individuals are in a country to pursue economic oppurtunities. This considers 12 different measures, which are then broken into four categories. They are:

  • Rule of Law (property rights, government integrity, judicial effectiveness)
  • Government Size (government spending, tax burden, fiscal health)
  • Regulatory Efficiency (business freedom, labor freedom, monetary freedom)
  • Open Markets (trade freedom, investment freedom, financial freedom)

Again, these are in no way 100% comprehensive, but they do provide a very good clue as to whether or not the world at large is improving. Works such as Steven Pinker's "Enlightenment Now" cover a bit more ground in terms of the breadth of statistics and measures considered, though it is not quite as heavy in the data analysis itself. As a continuation of this, one could consider every index on the website "Our World In Data", where each index is a compilation of numerous measures. This would create a summary statistic that encompasses many dozen, if not hundreds of separate measures. That is beyond the scope of this introductory tutorial on data analysis, though it is an interesting idea to consider.

Pandas can handle heterogenous data and has is a great way to get started with data analysis. Numpy provides us some mathematical functions while matplotlib will let us create plots and graphs. The cycler will allow us to cycle through colors as we create multiple lines on a single plot.

DATA MANAGEMENT AND CURATION

Wonerful. We have imported all of our data and we can get straight into the analysis... Or not. Look at the last set of data we have just imported. The first three rows are entirely "NaN", and the first column is also "NaN". Not only that, but we don't have the correct column names either. It looks like our column names are actually in the fourth row (index 3) in our data. This requires us to clean up and fix the data for our use. Often when we are collecting data, we will find that values are missing, the data format isn't what we need, or there are other problems. This is why we need to clean up our data to use it. That's what we will get started on below.

Great! Now we have cleaned up our data... sort of. If we take a look at the table we printed out, there are still a number of spaces filled with "NaN". There are three ways we could deal with this. We could:

  • Remove rows and columns with missing data
  • Encode missing data
  • Impute missing data

Each of these has some pros and cons. For our case, we will be using the first option: Remove the missing data. Fortunately, the Economic Freedom Summary Index acts as a summary statistic for all of the other measures in our table. This means that the organization collecting the data has already done some of their own imputation to create the index when certain measures in the index are missing, such as the case in in row 4052 seen above where tax compliance and Business regulations have missing values. There will still be missing data when even the index is missing, but it is an improvement nonetheless.

Now we have loaded all of our data and can start doing exploratory data analysis. We can't make any huge assumptions right at the beginning, so it is usually a good idea to start with some general plot of all of our values. If the plot ends up looking messy, or no meaningful conclusions can be drawn, then we can try a new method and experiment to find what we are looking for (assuming a correlation exists). If we do notice any patterns or interesting indications on our plots, we can focus on those sections and dive further in with our data analysis.

So, we've created some plots for each of the 6 measures we have decided to look at. However, they are rather messy, and it is difficult to draw any conclusions from what we have seen so far. The linear regressions we have created with the polyfit seems to indicate either no change, or a change for the better in most cases, but we can't say anything with certainty. This often happens when we are doing data analysis. Some type of plot or method may not give us the results we are looking for. However, the doesn't mean that we stop there. We continue to experiment and explore our data with different plots and other analysis methods. Lets think of a couple things we could do to get better information.

We could try making:

  • Violin Plots
  • Pie Charts
  • Bar Charts
  • Line Graphs
  • Residual Plots
  • Standardized Plots
  • Mean Plots

Each of these has pros and cons which may represent a certain piece of our data better than another. For example, we saw in our scatter plots above that each year that a measurement was taken, our plot has a line of blue dots. It is very difficult to parse how many points are actually being plotted. Using a violin plot, we could better understand the distribution each year. On the other hand, we could use the pie chart to show what fraction of countries are fall within different ranges of the different index's such as the Hunger Index. There are nearly infinite ways to represent data and it is up to us to choose one that is most helpful. For this tutorial, we will pick a few as examples.

First, lets take a look at the Global Hunger Index (what I have referred to as the Hunger Index). The official scale is seen below.

 GHI Severity Scale 9.9
low 10.019.9
moderate 20.034.9
serious 35.049.9
alarming 50.0
extremely alarming

It seems that while 100 is the maximum value (the worst possible value), anything above 50 is still "extremely alarming". Perhaps we could break this down into a pie chart to see how many nations are within a specific category during different years.

Finding out where your method fails is very important to determine how strong your conclusion is, or if it is even viable at all. As we create these pie charts, keep in mind any ways which our plot could misrepresent the data.

Lets take a look at the plots we have created. The percentage of nations in the extremely alarming range has dropped from 15.6% to 1%. The percentage of nations in the alarming range have gone from 30% to 5.8%. On the other hand, the number of nations in the serious range has increased from 24.0% to 43.3%. In 1992, 31% of nations were in the moderate to low range, while in 2018 50% of nations were in the moderate to low hunger index range.

Overall, we can say that these charts do indicate an overall decrease in the Hunger Index, therefore indicating an an average improvement in the hunger problem across the world. Now, as good data scientists, we should pick apart what we have created to see where things could go wrong. In our case, there are actually many reasons why this plot may NOT be the best way to represent the data. I have done so in this tutorial to give an example of the problems we could run into. The other plots we create will also have a number of potential issues which we will address to help the reader develop the skills needed to avoid these problems in the future.

To list a few issues:

  1. Not the same nations during the different measurements
    1. In 2018, there were 8 more nations measured than in 1992. This means some of the change we see could be the addition of these nations rather than an improvement in the nations originally measured
  2. Don't know the average fluctuation of Hunger Index values
    1. The change that we see between the two plots could actually be due to a normal fluctuation of the Hunger Index values. What if each year different nation's Hunger Index drastically changes based on the weather during that year? And what is 1992 was simply a bad year, while 2018 was a good year?
  3. Didn't calculate statistical significance
    1. This is related to the previous point. If we don't calculate statistical significance, we can't say for certain whether the change we have seen is meaningful.

While these are only a couple of the problems we may run into, nonetheless, they help us to understand what to look for. Again, keep these in mind as we make more plots for the each of the different measures we are looking at.

plt.ylabel("Cantril Happiness")
plt.title("Cantril Happiness vs Year")
Out[31]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Cantril Happiness vs Year')

Again, lets analyze this plot to see what we can find. We notice a couple things right at the beginning. One, the first set of data seems to be an outlier. This is likely due to which nations where given the survey during that first year. By 2006, we see a drastic change in the data compared to the previous year, which the average happiness dropping significantly. From 2006 to 2018, we see something interesting. The average happiness seems to increase just a little bit, but the shape of our distributions change more drastically. Near 2006 and 2007 we see that the distibution seems to clump near the bottom of the scale, and the distribution in 2017 and 2018 seems to be more centered. Consider ways we could improve the information we get from this plot. First we could try dropping the first year of measurement, as it seems to be a notable outlier. Then we could fit the data to a linear regression and create a residual plot. Depending on the shape of the residual plot, it could indicate the presence of an interaction between variables. Our data only has the country and the year, so we are limited in what we could test here, but in the future we could look for a different data set in order to do an analysis on the interaction. If the reader would like to look into this possible analysis more, I'd recommend the following link:

https://www.jmp.com/en_us/statistics-knowledge-portal/what-is-regression/simple-linear-regression-assumptions.html

This site helps explain how we can use residuals to analyze the effectivenessa nd validity of a linear regression. I will give an example later on, once we have created a unique plot for each of our data sets first.

Continuing on to our next set of data, we'll take a look at the homocide data set. Our first scatter plot of the homocide rate showed a clumping near the lower end, and a large skew toward the higher end. Lets make a violin plot to see exactly what this distribution is.

Out[37]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Homocide Rate vs Year')

Wow! This plot looks nothing like our previous violin plot of the Cantril Happiness Scale. We have a huge skew towards the high end, and massive clumping near the bottom. While in many cases we can try a linear regression, in this case we can say it would definitely be a bad choice. Why? It is because when making a linear regression, we make certain assumptions about the data. We assume:

  • Linearity: The relationship between X and the mean of Y is linear.
  • Homoscedasticity: The variance of residual is the same for any value of X.
  • Independence: Observations are independent of each other.
  • Normality: For any fixed value of X, Y is normally distributed.

In this case, we clearly don't have normality, a requirement for the lineear regression to be accurate. It is very difficult to determine if there has been any improvement based on this plot. Lets come back to this issue after we've completed our final plot and see if there are any tools or methods we could use in this scenario.

Again we have a very interesting plot. Our regression line once again seems to be a bad fit in this case. Our mean Development Index values are increasing in a way that seems either quadratic or exponential, which means we don't match the four requirements for a linear regression.

  • Linearity: The relationship between X and the mean of Y is linear.
  • Homoscedasticity: The variance of residual is the same for any value of X.
  • Independence: Observations are independent of each other.
  • Normality: For any fixed value of X, Y is normally distributed.

Here we fail due to non-linearity. However, in this case it is actually rather clear direction the graph is going. There is a very distinct increase of the Human Development Index across time. Looking at our original scatter plot, we also notice that the data points seem to be fairly consistent in that the points don't ever drastically vary between any two measurements, indicating a smooth change for the better.

HYPOTHESIS TESTING AND MACHINE LEARNING

We've gotten a good look at our data and now we have a good idea what we are looking for. At this point, we usually want to propose a hypothesis to test. In Hypothesis testing, we essentially have two possibilites, the Null Hypothesis and an Alternative Hypothesis. The Null Hypothesis proposes that there is no correlation between the variables. For our case, it would mean that there has been no improvement for the average human on Earth for the given time period or that any improvement that was measured is due to statistical variation and randomness. The Alternative hypothesis suggests that there is a meaningful and statistically significant correlation between the independent ande dependent variables. In our case, this means that the world has been improving meaningfully over the years in question. By performing a number of statistical methods, we can analyze with mathematical certainty whether or not the change of our vairous measures is statistically significant, or if it was due to sampling errors and randomness.

For the example in this tutorial, we will take a look at the Economic Freedom Summary Index. It is recommended that the reader try out hypothesis testing with the other data-sets to evaluate whether they agree with this example.

This residual plot shows us that from the period 2000-2018, the residuals from our linear regression are all roughly normalized which is very good, as that is one of the four assumptions for a linear regression. Lets now check that our regression for this range is statistically significant.

import statsmodels.api as sm

est2 = est.fit()

Looking at our output, we see that both our constant and our slope both have p values much less than 0.05, indicating that they are in fact statistically significant. If we had a p value greater than 0.05, it would indicate that there was not a significant different between the data and the Null Hypothesis, ie. no correlation. From this, we can confidently say that the Economic Freedom Summary Index has been increasing of the couple decades.

CONCLUSION

We've reached the end! Lets go over what we did and what we've learned about data analysis. We've managed to find data sources, import them into a pandas dataframe, we cleaned them up, and then did extensive exploratory analysis creating pie charts, bar graphs, line graphs, violin plots and more. Finally we used tested our hypothesis and found a p-value to determine the significance of our alternative hypothesis.

From this, we can conclude that the world at large has generally been improving over the last few decades. Over the time frames we looked at, worldwide hunger has gone down, economic freedom has increased, the gender wage gap has decreased, and the human development index (lifespan, quality of life, etc.) has gone up. The homocide rate and cantril happiness over these periods was much more difficult to discern any change and would require further analysis to determine the significance of any fluctuations. At the very least, they did not seem to go in the wrong direction by any significant margin.

As a continuation and extension of this tutorial, the reader is encouraged to expound on the data and analysis done here. The breadth of data looked at here was extensive and there are many places where a driven data scientists could take a look into. Has the homocide rate in each individual country remained relatively constant, or have the countries with high homocide rates been changing, creating no net change on a large scale even as individual nations change greatly? What is the interaction between the gender wage gap and homocide rate? Between the economic freedom and happiness? There are many relationships and patterns which we could continue to look at. We are only limited by what we can imagine doing.
